   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422593_1825-03-09_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <date when="1825-03-09"/> March 9<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1825 </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SpriT1">Sir</persName><!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               This horrible affair at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Eton_ENK">Eton</placeName><lb/>
               has I am convinced filled<lb/>
               your head &amp; heart as it<lb/>
               has ours - Even in the<lb/>
               midst of the Business of<lb/>
               the nation you are so good<lb/>
               a father that I am certain<lb/>
               it would for some hours<lb/>
               at least prevent you from<lb/>
               thinking of any thing else<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               I wish every parent who<lb/>
               has a son at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Eton_ENK">Eton</placeName> would<lb/>
               send for him home at<lb/>
               once till some reform<lb/>
               is made<lb/>
              </p>
            <p>
               Surely some good will<lb/>
               be brought from this great<lb/>
               evil by - who? - Ask<lb/>
               yourself - by such men<lb/>
               as you who have power<lb/>
               to raise your voice in the<lb/>
               cause of helpless youth<lb/>
               
            </p>
            <p>
               A Master of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Eton_ENK">Eton</placeName> standing<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422593_1825-03-09_page02.jpg"/>
               by while this barbarous<lb/>
               deed was done - was<lb/>
               doing for two hours! -<lb/></p>
               <p>A boy of 15! - set on <del>&amp;</del><lb/>
               <unclear>betted</unclear> upon by his <choice><orig>compa-<lb/>
                  nions</orig><reg>companions</reg></choice> - as if he were a<lb/>
               game cock - his offer to<lb/>
               make it up forbidden<lb/>
               by those who betted <hi rend="underline">upon</hi><lb/>
               his life - Drenched with<lb/>
               brandy! - an incredible<lb/>
               quantity! Enough to<lb/>
               have killed him without<lb/>
               a blow - Oh if he was<lb/>
               not murdered what is<lb/>
               murder? - There was no<lb/>
               malice - no - but there was<lb/>
               death ensuing <del>from</del> &amp;<lb/>
               caused from being <choice><orig>engag<lb/>
                  ed</orig><reg>engaged</reg></choice> in an unlawful<lb/>
               act - <lb/>
               </p>
            <p>
               Gambling - <choice><orig>drunken-<lb/>
                  ness</orig><reg>drunkenness</reg></choice> - cruelty - what<lb/>
               a complication of vice<lb/>
               
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422593_1825-03-09_page03.jpg"/>
               
               and how could any<lb/>
               <del>brother</del> man any <choice><orig>mas-<lb/>
                  ter</orig><reg>master</reg></choice> any brother stand<lb/>
               by for 2 hours &amp; see<lb/>
               this brutal savage scene<lb/>
               - How could human<lb/>
               nature stand it? -<lb/>
               And these are the sights<lb/>
               which M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WyndW1">Wyndham</persName><lb/>
               thought good for the<lb/>
               courage of the British<lb/>
               nation -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               If I do not much <choice><orig>mis-<lb/>
                  take</orig><reg>mistake</reg></choice> your character &amp;<lb/>
               your power you will<lb/>
               not let this horrid act<lb/>
               rest as a disgrace upon<lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK"/>England in the eyes of the<lb/>
               whole civilised world<lb/>
               as it must unless some<lb/>
               public of indignation be<lb/>
               raised against it<lb/>
               
            </p>
            <p>
               <del>Howsay</del> This poor<lb/>
               youths death may lead<lb/>
               
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Morgan_422593_1825-03-09_page04.jpg"/>
               
               to a great good, if good &amp;<lb/>
               wise men exert <choice><orig>them-<lb/>
                  selves</orig><reg>themselves</reg></choice> - now - <hi rend="underline">now</hi>! When<lb/>
               all hearts are melted<lb/>
               by pity or fired with <choice><orig>indig<lb/>
                  nation</orig><reg>indignation</reg></choice> - Oh do not let the<lb/>
               moment for making an<lb/>
               impression pass - This<lb/>
               may lead to the reform<lb/>
               of this horrible system in<lb/>
               public schools - Think<lb/>
               of your own sons - It<lb/>
               will some time be their<lb/>
               turns to go to them -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               There is one fortunate<lb/>
               circumstance in this horrid<lb/>
               affair that both the young<lb/>
               men are -<hi rend="underline">were</hi> <add>sons of</add> men of<lb/>
               family &amp; consequence<lb/>
            </p>
            <p>
               My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SpriT1">Sir</persName> pray write<lb/>
               to me &amp; confirm my belief<lb/>
               that your feelings &amp; <choice><orig>indigna<lb/>
                  tion</orig><reg>indignation</reg></choice> have been roused as<lb/>
               strongly as our own<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               Ever sincerely y<hi rend="superscript">s</hi><lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
            </closer>
         </div>
